      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and I've run into a serious issue. The system has a slow memory leak that only shows up after about 4-6 hours of continuous operation. It's not crashing immediately, just gradually exhausting the heap until the watchdog triggers a reset.\n\nHere is the core loop where we handle sensor data processing:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data(const SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet == nullptr) return;\n\n    // Allocate buffer for processing\n    uint8_t* processing_buffer = new uint8_t[packet->size];\n    \n    // Copy data\n    std::memcpy(processing_buffer, packet->data, packet->size);\n\n    // Perform complex DSP operations\n    apply_filter(processing_buffer, packet->size);\n    validate_checksum(processing_buffer, packet->size);\n\n    // Data is sent to the telemetry module\n    telemetry_module.send(processing_buffer, packet->size);\n\n    // TODO: Free buffer? \n    // I thought I handled this in the telemetry module destructor or via a smart pointer, \n    // but I can't track it down.\n}\n```\n\nCan you give me a systematic approach to debugging this in a resource-constrained environment? I don't have access to Valgrind on this hardware.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
